title: For Sale:  P14 Enfield - Very Nice Condition .303 Brit
postcontent: For sale is a P14 Enfield. Rifle was manufactured in 1916, right in the middle of WW1. The United Sates was contracted through Great Britain to build these rifles during WW1. Rifle shoots .303 Brit. This is the predessesor to the much more common 1917 Enfield. Rifle was manufactured by ERA. Eddystone Remington Arms. Eddystone was a subsidiary of Remington that souly made Enfields. The United States didn't enter WW1 until 1917. Up until then, the USA was just manufacturing loads of stuff for allies. The P14s were primarily used as sniper rifles during WW1. This rifle has one of the nicest triggers I've ever felt on an old military rifle. Bore is very nice. These rifles had one of the strongest actions during WW1. P14/P17s are commonly built into big bore rifles because of how strong their action is. It's in very nice condition for being 102 years old. Whoever this rifle was issued to took very good care of it. Rifle is all matching numbers, even the barrel and the rear site. It also has its original volley sites. Most were lost during refurbishments, so this is a not so common feature. This rifle has a very hard to see import mark underneath the muzzle end of the barrel, so you know this rifle was actually shipped over to Europe and used. It wasn't just some trainer or arsenal rifle kept in the US. Very neat rifle, lots of history, can't say enough great things about it.Asking $800 OBO, shoot me a text at REDACTED if you're interested, can send plenty of pictures

title: For Sale:  M1 Carbine Paratrooper Scammer/Thief Alert
postcontent: Guys.  Be forewarned.  Sorry for the detail of this but it might save someone.  The nutbag who is listing is rifle is a scammer and is likely trying to cheat someone out of cash.  I know because approx 2 months ago when this thing was listed originally I contacted him and we agreed to meet at the place of his picking to look over the trades which was a rocks throw from the gunshop where the transfer was supposed to take place.When we met, he looked over my trade and then I examined this rifle closely. While examining the condition of the rifle ( more on that in a sec ) he began to say he wasnt familiar with the law and didnt know how to complete this trade.  RED FLAG ALERT,  A topic already agreed upon during our emails when we selected the FFL to use.  I informed him of the process and when I said lets head over to the gunshop,  he began saying he didnt have any cash and upon further disclosure he had no means of payment for his end of the transfer. RED FLAG ALERT,  we agreed to meet the next day at the gunshop which was local to him.  Later that evening, he sent an email that someone had bought the rifle. RED FLAG ALERT.  Well, low and behold now the very same ad is listed again.  If that's not enough, the rifle condition is suspect.  Clean as his ad says perhaps.  Shot out is more like it, the action has heavy wear.  The wooden flutes that hold the arms of the retractable stock in place have cracks which will make an already loose stock even more sloppy.Value.  Way overpriced.  Anyone who can type the word google will find these in like or better condition for $350 on average as Plainsfield M1's are commercial clones and were not built with GI critical parts.  Avoid this guy or find yourself cheated.  You have been warned.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Stringers
postcontent: A stringer is a person who tells you that they want to purchase your firearm. Then you don't hear from them for 3 or 4 days. Then you get an email every 3-4 days confirming that they want to purchase, but don't save it for them. Then they want to set up a time to do a deal. Then they are so busy, like their time is worth more than yours. From start to finish, this is weeks, and then they end up telling you that they changed their mind. Lots of them on here lately. Just got done with one who's initials are KK. 2 weeks jagging around. Watch out. If someone is legit, 2 days transaction time at most unless there are extenuating circumstances.
